data.content:
## Migration: `TimedExecutor` → .NET 8

### Pattern Classification

This is **Timeout enforcement** — aborting a thread that exceeds a time limit. It also contains a **ThreadAbortException catch with ResetAbort**, which swallowed the abort to keep the thread alive.

### Why This Breaks on .NET 8

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — the runtime no longer supports forcible thread termination. `Thread.ResetAbort()` is equally dead. The entire timeout mechanism is non-functional.

---

### Migrated Code

```csharp
using System;
using System.Threading;
using System.Threading.Tasks;

public class TimedExecutor
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Executes work with a timeout using cooperative cancellation.
    /// The work delegate MUST check the CancellationToken for timely cancellation.
    /// </summary>
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            // Task.Run respects OperationCanceledException thrown by
            // token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested() inside the delegate.
            Task<T> task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);

            // Block until completion or cancellation.
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            // Unwrap single-exception aggregates for cleaner call-site handling.
            throw ex.InnerExceptions[0];
        }
    }

    /// <summary>
    /// Async version — preferred in modern .NET code.
    /// </summary>
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await work(cts.Token).WaitAsync(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

---

### What Changed and Why

| Old (.NET Framework) | New (.NET 8) | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `new Thread(...)` | `Task.Run(...)` | Thread pool is more efficient; no manual thread lifecycle |
| `thread.Abort()` | `CancellationTokenSource(timeout)` | `Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 6+ |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` | Cooperative cancellation throws `OCE`, not `TAE` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | *(removed)* | No equivalent needed — cancellation is voluntary |
| `thread.Join(timeout)` | `CancelAfter` via constructor | Timeout is built into the token source |

---

### Caller Migration

```csharp
// BEFORE — fire-and-forget delegate, abort kills it forcibly
var executor = new TimedExecutor();
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    () => ExpensiveComputation(),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

// AFTER — delegate must accept and check the token
var executor = new TimedExecutor();
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    ct =>
    {
        // Check the token at regular intervals inside your work
        for (int i = 0; i < 1_000_000; i++)
        {
            ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // <-- checkpoint
            ProcessChunk(i);
        }
        return FinalResult();
    },
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

---

### Critical Pitfalls

1. **Cancellation is cooperative, not preemptive.** The old code could kill *any* thread instantly. The new code only works if `work` checks the token. If it calls a blocking API that ignores tokens (e.g., `Thread.Sleep`, raw socket read), cancellation stalls until that call returns.

2. **Don't forget to dispose `CancellationTokenSource`.** It holds timer resources when created with a timeout. The `using` statement handles this.

3. **Pass the token through the entire call chain.** If `work` calls helper methods, each must forward `ct`. One missing link breaks the chain:
   ```csharp
   // BAD — helper ignores cancellation
   int Compute() { /* long work, no token */ }

   // GOOD
   int Compute(CancellationToken ct) { ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); /* ... */ }
   ```

4. **Don't catch and swallow `OperationCanceledException`.** The old code caught `ThreadAbortException` and called `ResetAbort()` to keep running. In the new model, if you catch `OCE` inside the work delegate and swallow it, the timeout mechanism silently fails — the task completes "successfully" with a wrong result.

5. **Truly uncooperative code can't be cancelled in-process.** If you're wrapping a third-party library that does a 60-second blocking call with no token support, your only option is to run it in a **separate process** and call `Process.Kill()`. This is the .NET 8 equivalent of the old `Thread.Abort` for uncooperative code.
